ous for HbS alele (which in homozygous state causes sickle-cell anaemia) can catch the parasite, but the chances are bigger, that the infected cells will be phagocytized by macrophages and the parasite will be unable to reproduce in them.&quot;"},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user21723"},"score":0,"post_id":43314,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/78GJV.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19650,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19650/yvide","reputation":1952,"display_name":"YviDe"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455457252,"comment_id":74931,"body":"So I do not understand why chances are greater that the infected cells will be phagocytosed by macrophages. I agree that my query is quite similar, but I am unable to fully comprehend the posted answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3e5f0d71d85cff28bc4a479a1635bb7b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16371,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16371/matej-pribis","reputation":174,"display_name":"Matej Pribis"},"score":1,"post_id":43314,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455889706,"comment_id":75291,"body":"Cells only with HbS (Form of hemoglobin responsible for sickle cell anaemia) have limited lifespan , have changes in shape (due to HbS polymerisation) AND consequently are phagocyted. The heterozygots for HbS have some concentrations of this protein in their RBC, these cells have a bit shortened lifespan, but otherwise can function normally. After infection of such RBC by parasite however, cell has an increased chance of sickling.Sickle cell will probably be phagocytized. Therefore the parazite won&#39;t be able to reproduce. Look on an illustration in the original answer, and its article for ref."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43314/does-sickle-cell-anaemia-protect-a-victim-against-malaria","last_activity_date":1455444617,"creation_date":1455444617,"answer_