user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1455414252,"creation_date":1455413568,"body":"<p>This question shows so much misunderstanding in evolutionary biology (no offense) that it is hard to fully answer. As @MattDMo suggested, you will benefit from having a look to an introductory course to evolutionary biology such as <a href=\"http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/home.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">Understanding Evolution<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>But what about the trees? They must also come from that single cellular bacteria<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The Most Recent Common Ancestor (MRCA) of animals and plants was not a bacteria but single-celled <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eukaryote\" rel=\"nofollow\">eukaryote<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Once you'd have a look at the course <a href=\"http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/home.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">Understanding Evolution<\/a>, you might want to have a look at the tree of life on <a href=\"http://tolweb.org/tree/\" rel=\"nofollow\">tolweb.org<\/a> for example<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Since when they got separated from animals?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The MRCA of animals and plants lived about 1.6 billion years ago.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>What made them to be so much different than animals?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Time has passed and with time different lineages diverse through a number of different processes. By increasing your understanding of evolutionary biology (<a href=\"http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/home.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">Understanding Evolution<\/a> again), you will be able to understand these processes much better.<\/p>\n\n<p>Note that while with time (1.6 billion years) genetic differences have accumulated between animals and plants, there are still a large number of similitudes. Some of these similitudes are also shared with other organisms such as bacteria for example and some are not shared with bacteria. Here is a short, non-exhaustive list of similitudes:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Both use <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA\" rel=\"nofollow\">DNA<\/a> to store genetic information<\/li>\n<li>Both use <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenosine_triphosphate\" rel=\"nofollow\">Adenosine Triphosphate (ATP)<\/a> for transferring energy within cells<\/li>\n<li>Both use lots of water.<\/li>\n<li>Both have a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_membrane\" rel=\"nofollow\">cell membrane<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both undergo <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cellular_respiration\" rel=\"nofollow\">cellular respiration<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both undergo <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">mitosis<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both undergo <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meiosis\" rel=\"nofollow\">meiosis<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both have their DNA contained in a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_nucleus\" rel=\"nofollow\">nucleus<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both have <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endoplasmic_reticulum\" rel=\"nofollow\">endoplasmic reticulum<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both have DNA organized in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chromosome\" rel=\"nofollow\">chromosomes<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both contain <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitochondrion\" rel=\"nofollow\">mitochondria<\/a><\/li>\n<li>Both have <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Histone\" rel=\"nofollow\">histones<\/a><\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Note by the way, that I focused exclusively on similitudes that are caused by shared ancestry and not by <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convergent_evolution\" rel=\"nofollow\">convergent evolution<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Besides, apparently their evolution is very slow, isn't it?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The terms slow and fast are obviously relative. To discuss really how fast is evolution, you would need to know what evolution is and you would need to know a little more about the processes that drive evolution.<\/p>\n\n<p>In very short and largely simplified: Evolution is a change in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allele\" rel=\"nofollow\">allele<\/a> frequency (at a given <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locus_(genetics)\" rel=\"nofollow\">locus<\/a>) trough time. Such change occurs every second in a big population. However, the evolution of a large <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phenotype\" rel=\"nofollow\">phenotypic trait<\/a> that was previously completely inexistant may take much more time depending on how much <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Genetic_variance\" rel=\"nofollow\">genetic variance<\/a>, you have to start with, depending on the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutation_rate\" rel=\"nofollow\">mutation rate<\/a>, depending on the number of mutations required, depending on the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Selection_coefficient\" rel=\"nofollow\">selection coefficient<\/a> for each of these steps and depending on a number of different things.<\/p>\n\n<p>So the answer to \"How much time does it takes for evolution to occur\" varies between a fraction of a second and infinity depending on what you mean exactly.<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Why are they lagging behind in the race of living organism?<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>I don't understand this question. I don't know who is \"they\", I don't know what you mean by \"behind\" and I don't know what you mean by \"the race of living organism\". <\/p>\n","answer_id":43306,"question_id":43272,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1455414252}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43272/why-plants-and-animals-are-so-different-even-though-they-come-from-the-same-ance","last_activity_date":1455414252,"creation_date":1455277046,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why plants and animals are so different even though they come from the same ancestors?","body":"<p>All the documentaries I have watched, books I have read so far on the starting of life on earth only talk about animals. The very first life form on earth was bacteria. Then evolution took us this far. But what about the trees? They must also come from that single cellular bacteria. Since when they got separated from animals? What made them to be so much different than animals? Besides, apparently their evolution is very slow, isn't it? Why are they lagging behind in the race of living organism?<\/p>\n","question_id":43272,"tags":["evolution"],"score":-2,"down_vote_count":3,"is_answered":true,"view_count":72,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d3f79bbfcfe613c1a0dc872193c15a0f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21721,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21721/filip","reputation":217,"display_name":"filip"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":12,"post_id":43095,"edited":false,"creation_date":1454869875,"comment_id":74374,"body":"Calling it a simple trick that the brain should be able to do is really kind of missing the entire point of the answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":11,"post_id":43095,"edited":false,"creation_date":1454871462,"comment_id":74375,"body":"Maybe it would be a simple trick, but what would be the evolutionary benefit to such a trick?  The visual system works quite differently, detecting change/movement (which probably equals threat) far more easily than static scenery.  The human eye has built-in motion - saccades - that allow it to see more clearly.  IIRC (though I can&#39;t quickly find a reference) if you electronically compensate for the saccades, so the visual field stays fixed, everything washes out and you&#39;re effectively blind."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":0,"post_id":43095,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1454874466,"comment_id":74382,"body":"@jamesqf - Thank you. I guess my answer was too vague, that &quot;not be[ing] able to detect change rapidly [is] something that would be most inconvenient.&quot; Your comment adds a lot to the answer."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":4,"post_id":43095,"edited":false,"creation_date":1454909247,"comment_id":74427,"body":"Also think in terms of evolution.  Say you&#39;re a species evolving towards being nocturnal, and &quot;need&quot; to improve your low-light vision.  The easiest route is simply to increase the size of the eye.  You could also add a reflective layer, e.g. the &quot; tapetum lucidum&quot;."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/61b50025bf8456821ba336828c25dafd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20047,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20047/tobia-tesan","reputation":125,"display_name":"Tobia Tesan"},"score":3,"post_id":43095,"edited":false,"