 alternations between selection for proliferation and selection for survival as the populations breaks through one carrying capacity after another. Of interest to me, is the overall shape of the growth curve as several sigmoids -- with each corresponding to a different serial resource limitation. However, this growth curve is a cartoon and not a measurement of some empirical system. <strong>Are there examples of such growth curves in the empirical literature on cancer?<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>An ideal case would be in a well studied animal model (or humans), with a corresponding analysis of which resource limitation was overcome at each step. With at least two, but preferably more, resource limitations in series. However, I will also be satisfied with answers from cell lines grown <em>in vitro<\/em>, since growth curves are usually easier to measure there. <\/p>\n\n<p>Aktipis, C. A., Boddy, A. M., Gatenby, R. A., Brown, J. S., &amp; Maley, C. C. (2013). <a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/nrc3606\" rel=\"nofollow\">Life history trade-offs in cancer evolution<\/a>. <em>Nature Reviews Cancer<\/em>, 13(12): 883-892.<\/p>\n","question_id":43245,"tags":["evolution","cancer","ecology","growth"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":90,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1455206810},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/769OU.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21811,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21811/odddev","reputation":149,"display_name":"OddDev"},"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"Aravona"},"score":0,"post_id":43231,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455177142,"comment_id":74692,"body":"This might get a better answer on biology or maybe even pets? But it&#39;s probably due to the type of fur, huskies don&#39;t seem to get this either. Most dog breeds are bred now for look. They retain the high fat concentration in their paws to prevent their pads freezing though."},{"owner"