te":1455227098,"comment_id":74741,"body":"When your eyes are closed in bright light, you see red because the light shines through the blood vessels inside your eyelids. Eventually this will &quot;wear out&quot; your red cone cells so that they stop sending signals to the brain (a form of sensory adaptation). This results in you only seeing blue and green for a few minutes after opening your eyes until your red cone cells are able to recover and begin firing again. I am not sure why this question is on hold, it seems like a good question to me. Maybe I missed something..."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Vgu4A.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21818,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21818/vrugtehagel","reputation":111,"display_name":"vrugtehagel"},"score":1,"post_id":43244,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Zl6dm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13496,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13496/cdb","reputation":1164,"display_name":"CDB","accept_rate":100},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455228960,"comment_id":74744,"body":"I also don&#39;t really know why it&#39;s being closed. It says opinion-based, but I don&#39;t really find where I put in my opinion. However, this is my first question on this forum, so I guess I&#39;m not familiar with your customs. Thanks for the reply though, you answered my question!"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/Zl6dm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":13496,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13496/cdb","reputation":1164,"display_name":"CDB","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":43244,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455297175,"comment_id":74842,"body":"My pleasure. :)"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43244/why-do-i-see-the-world-in-blue-when-i-open-my-eyes","last_activity_date":1455201750,"creation_date":1455201750,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why do I see the world in blue when I open my eyes?","body":"<p>So I was standing outside, waiting for the train. I was tired so I closed my eyes for a while. Then when I opened them, the world was a lot more blue than it normally is - why is this? I tried it a couple more times to be sure that it wasn't just a mistake, which confirmed it, as the world kept being blue (of course, not permanent, it slowly gets back to the \"normal\" colors).<\/p>\n\n<p>I'd appreciate a simple explanation, as I'm not a biology or physics student. I only have a very basic understanding of both subjects. Thanks in advance!<\/p>\n","question_id":43244,"tags":["eyes","light"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"primarily opinion-based","is_answered":false,"view_count":45,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/55DUG.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15368,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15368/rockpaperlizard","reputation":169,"display_name":"RockPaperLizard"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2dfe5daa4030cdda49de92543894fd65?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21816,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21816/oleksandr-papchenko","reputation":101,"display_name":"Oleksandr Papchenko"},"score":0,"post_id":43234,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455192018,"comment_id":74702,"body":"I think spores can cause problems only in immunodeficienc individuals."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/55DUG.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15368,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15368/rockpaperlizard","reputation":169,"display_name":"RockPaperLizard"},"score":0,"post_id":43234,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2dfe5daa4030cdda49de92543894fd65?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21816,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21816/oleksandr-papchenko","reputation":101,"display_name":"Olek