Metathoracic scent gland ostiole with well-developed peritreme (Fig. 20). Fore wing: apical angle of corium narrowly rounded. Abdomen: intersegmental sutures between abdominal sternites 4/5 and 5/6 laterally strongly curved anteriad. Legs: fore femora with small denticles ventrally.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/9Vzsu.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/9Vzsu.jpg\" alt=\"Melamphus\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p><em>Sources:<\/em>\n<a href=\"http://psybugs.biota.biodiv.tw/files/biota_psybugs/fig.1-2.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://psybugs.biota.biodiv.tw/files/biota_psybugs/fig.1-2.jpg<\/a>\n<a href=\"http://psybugs.biota.biodiv.tw/pages/598\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://psybugs.biota.biodiv.tw/pages/598<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":43131,"question_id":43116,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7258cbf9bfcfd112bb90d1e55f8dd1a7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19468,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19468/rha","reputation":316,"display_name":"RHA"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"score":2,"post_id":43228,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455181043,"comment_id":74694,"body":"Indeed so, see e.g. <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00265-002-0524-9\" rel=\"nofollow\">Sch&#246;fl &amp; Taborsky. 2002. <i>Prolonged tandem formation in firebugs (Pyrrhocoris apterus) serves mate-guarding<\/i><\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/7258cbf9bfcfd112bb90d1e55f8dd1a7?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19468,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19468/rha","reputation":316,"display_name":"RHA"},"score":0,"post_id":43228,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/v5upF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3624,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3624/fileunderwater","reputation":10502,"display_name":"fileunderwater"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455181459,"comment_id":74695,"body":"@fileunderwater Good find! I&#39;ll add that to the answer."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1455181908,"creation_date":1455177218,"body":"<p><strong>As to them 'always' walking in pairs:<\/strong> \nI had a different firebug (Pyrrhocoris apterus) living around my previous house. They do not always walk in pairs, especially early in spring i've often seen them walking alone. In summer pairs become more common indeed.  <\/p>\n\n<p>You will probably have guessed that the pairing has to do with sexual reproduction. The question however is <em>why they stay together so long<\/em>, as mating in insects usually takes no more then a few minutes. This is called mate-guarding, the male wants to make sure that the female deposits eggs with his sperm and stays with her until she has layed her eggs, as shown <a href=\"http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs00265-002-0524-9\" rel=\"nofollow\">Shöfl &amp; Taborsky 2002<\/a> (thanks to @fileunderwater for this reference.)\nThis behaviour is not uncommon for insects, and is also well documented for dragonflies (odonata, e.g. Corbet 1962).<\/p>\n","answer_id":43228,"question_id":43116,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1455181908}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43116/are-these-lovebugs","last_activity_date":1455181908,"creation_date":1454910713,"answer_count":3,"title":"Are these lovebugs?","body":"<p>I used to see these insects frequently in Chennai and Bangalore (South India). I just would like to know if this is a kind of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lovebug\">lovebug<\/a>. The lovebug as mentioned in the Wikipedia page is, however, different in appearance, although they too are walking as pairs.<\/p>\n\