nd the metabolism of organism living in extreme depths in other ways: <\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Under pressure, <a href=\"http://www.pnas.org/content/96/26/14848.full\" rel=\"nofollow\">the folding and unfolding kinetics of proteins can change drastically<\/a>. Which means, that the protein structures may need adaptation to great pressures.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Under pressure the <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3938881\" rel=\"nofollow\">fluidity of the cell membrane lipids changes<\/a>, requiring adaptations in membrane lipid composition.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>In conclusion, I would say that the pressure in the deep sea does not directly affect the size of cells but rather their metabolism.<\/p>\n\n<p>Edit: I just saw the second part in the heading of your question (\"and can they survive in shallow water?\"). Again, I'll <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deep_sea_creature#Deep_sea_research\" rel=\"nofollow\">quote Wikipedia<\/a>:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The extreme difference in pressure between the sea floor and the surface makes the creature's survival on the surface near impossible;<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>The reason for this is that pressure works thermodynamically in many ways similar to temperature: As explained above, changing the pressure significantly alters reaction kinetics and phase transitions. Thus, the whole metabolism has to adapt to increased pressure (similarly to the adaptation to increased temperature). <\/p>\n\n<p>However, at least some deep sea creatures seem to be able to adapt to surface pressure if the transition is not too abrupt (from the same wikipedia article as above):<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>A marine biologist, Jeffery Drazen, has explored a solution, a pressurized fish trap. This captures a deep-water creature, and adjusts its internal pressure slowly to surface level as the creature is brought to the surface, in the hope that the creature can adjust.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n","answer_id":43127,"question_id":42923,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1455112032}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/42923/are-the-cells-structures-of-deep-sea-fish-different-and-can-they-survive-in-s","last_activity_date":1455112032,"creation_date":1454412136,"answer_count":1,"title":"Are the cells (structures) of deep sea fish different? And can they survive in shallow water?","body":"<p>In the deep oceans the pressure is enormous. But still there are fish living. But are the cells of them different from fish who just live at the surface of waters?<\/p>\n\n<p>For example, are the cells smaller because of the pressure? And if so, does that influence the inner metabolism? If not, how do they succeed in maintaining their size?<\/p>\n","question_id":42923,"tags":["physiology","zoology","ichthyology"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":1,"is_answered":true,"view_count":86,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1454922871},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/27c05ca289f93699e5b43318b28ecd39?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":21788,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21788/diogo-b-provete","reputation":1,"display_name":"Diogo B Provete"},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43190/how-to-incorporate-intraspecific-variation-in-discrete-characters-in-comparative","last_activity_date":1455111925,"creation_date":1455111925,"answer_count":0,"title":"How to incorporate intraspecific variation in discrete characters in comparative analyzes?","body":"<p>I'd like to run a multivariate analysis (<a href=\"http://www.cef.ulaval.ca/uploads/Membres/PavoineEtal2011.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Pavoine et al. 2011<\/a>) that aims to disentagle the effect of environmental gradients on traits, considering its autocorrelation with phylogeny and space. It uses the RLQ approach and works with both discrete and continuous traits. However, I don't know how to incorporate intraspecific variation in discrete traits. \nFor example, I recorded categories of pigmentation on organs of several amphibians, but for some species, these categories vary among individuals. One way would be including individuals as polytomies at the species level, but this would make the test quite hard to interpret.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you in advance,\nDiogo<\/p>\n","question_id":43190,"tags":["evolution","data","methods","macroevolution"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":4,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aff0866587273eeae903c6bd2715b717?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20146,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20146/jack-m","reputation":116,"display_name":"Jack M"},"closed_date":1455168606,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":43187,"edited":false,"creation_date":1455109286,"comment_id":74607,"body":"A pre-existing answer is linked in the above comment. I admit it doesn&#39;t cover the methods used to determine it&#39;s really cleansing. However, you cannot ask a fly why its doing something. One can just infer. As a consequence, there&#39;s no scientific literature on this afaik."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aff0866587273eeae903c6bd2715b717?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":20146,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20146/jack-m","reputation":116,"display_name":"Jack M"},"score":0,"post_id":43187,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455110550,"comment_id":74609,"body":"@Christiaan Well, you coul