a used in convolutional neural networks for deep learning of images.<\/p>\n\n<p>On the other hand, this one, for the primate retina, states that there is no such overlap:\n<a href=\"http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0042698995001670\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0042698995001670<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>So do primate RGCs have overlapping RFs? If not, how does the primate visual system deal with this sparse input? How does it fill in the blanks?<\/p>\n","question_id":43144,"tags":["vision","neurophysiology","human-eye"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":20,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1454974119},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ed8e80cdafd930c6f3c1cd94e33709bc?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":21758,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/21758/xxwangl","reputation":4,"display_name":"XXWANGL"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/acb3c0063d438705f86396a8abc1b04a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":12877,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/12877/cmosychuk","reputation":4410,"display_name":"CMosychuk"},"score":1,"post_id":43149,"edited":false,"creation_date":1454970576,"comment_id":74526,"body":"Put bluntly, soluble proteins have shielded as many hydrophobic residues in their sequence as possible from the solvent (say cytosol, primarily aqueous). As the solvent then has access primarily to hydrophilic residues, the protein is largely soluble. Denatured proteins with large, exposed regions of hydrophobic residues become insoluble because hydrophobic molecules do not dissolve in water. As this is what amounts to a homework question, however, do keep in mind for subsequent questions that this site requires some personal effort to obtain a good answer!"}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43149/why-do-denatured-proteins-tend-to-be-less-soluble-t