se,"creation_date":1454997791,"comment_id":74536,"body":"The values that you mentioned are not absolute. There is certainly a range. If you look at plants, the composition of carbohydrates will be high because of the cellulose cell wall."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/243ca59af79f85064c119866fb5b4eb6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":843,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/843/alan2here","reputation":163,"display_name":"alan2here"},"score":0,"post_id":43132,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/SjvUL.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":3340,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3340/wysiwyg","reputation":23153,"display_name":"WYSIWYG","accept_rate":80},"edited":false,"creation_date":1455014296,"comment_id":74551,"body":"Thanks @WYSIWYG, it&#39;s useful information."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/43132/lifeforms-concentrations-of-the-categories-of-macromolecules-and-lipids","last_activity_date":1454946131,"creation_date":1454945075,"answer_count":0,"title":"Lifeforms concentrations of the categories of macromolecules, and Lipids","body":"<p>Lifeforms are formed of large, modular, organic molecules called macromolecules, large organic molecules called Lipids, and simpler molecules such as H2O.<\/p>\n\n<p>Macromolecules are commonly grouped into the following categorises:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Protien<\/li>\n<li>Nucleic Acid<\/li>\n<li>Carbohydrate<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>The concentrations of these types of molecule by mass, in a dehydrated (therefore dead) \"E. coli\" are:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Protein: 55%\nNucleic Acid: 23%\nCarbohydrate: 0%\nLipid: 9%\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>From: <a href=\"http://book.bionumbers.org/what-is-the-macromolecular-composition-of-the-cell\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://book.bionumbers.org/what-is-the-macromolecular-composition-of-the-cell<\/a><\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><strong>Q:<\/strong> Repeating the above table for other lifeforms, for the whole organism if it is multi-cellular, can examples be given of lifeforms that are particular outliers?<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>I have been unable to find much more useful information, however this data probably exists, I could find nothing for larger lifeforms such an animals. Around 60% of a cells cytosol is proteins, however this is by volume, not by mass.<\/p>\n","question_id":43132,"tags":["molecular-biology","proteins","microbiology","lipids","carbohydrates"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":28,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1454946131}]}